To see a "real-time" project scenario, let's simulate a log-processing architecture.
In this setup, we have a Web App (the Producer) that generates data and a Python Script (the Consumer) running in a separate pod that fetches that data via the ClusterIP service.
1. The "Project" Setup: Web App
First, we'll run a web app that serves a simple JSON status page.
# producer-deployment.yaml
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: web-producer
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: backend-api
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: backend-api
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: app
        image: nginx
        command: ["/bin/sh", "-c"]
        # This creates a "real-time" mock data file
        args: ["echo '{\"status\": \"active\", \"logs\": \"all-clear\"}' > /usr/share/nginx/html/data.json && nginx -g 'daemon off;'"]
---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: api-service
spec:
  selector:
    app: backend-api
  ports:
    - port: 80
      targetPort: 80

Apply this: kubectl apply -f producer-deployment.yaml
2. The Automation Script (The "Work")
Instead of just using curl, we will use a Python script inside another pod to programmatically "fetch" and process this data.
Save this as fetch_data.py:
import requests
import time

# The URL uses the ClusterIP Service name
SERVICE_URL = "http://api-service/data.json"

def monitor_backend():
    print(f"Connecting to {SERVICE_URL}...")
    while True:
        try:
            response = requests.get(SERVICE_URL)
            if response.status_code == 200:
                data = response.json()
                print(f"[REAL-TIME UPDATE] Backend Status: {data['status']}")
            else:
                print("Failed to fetch data.")
        except Exception as e:
            print(f"Error connecting: {e}")
        
        time.sleep(5) # Wait 5 seconds before next fetch

if __name__ == "__main__":
    monitor_backend()

3. Run the Automation Pod
Now, run a Python container and pass this script into it to see the ClusterIP in action.
Step A: Run a Python pod in interactive mode:
kubectl run automation-worker --image=python:3.9 -i --tty --rm -- /bin/bash

Step B: Inside the new pod prompt, install requests and run the work:
# Inside the container:
pip install requests > /dev/null
cat <<EOF > monitor.py
# (Paste the Python code from above here)
EOF

python3 monitor.py

Why this is "Real Project" Work:
• Decoupling: Your Python script doesn't need to know the IP addresses of the 3 Nginx pods. It only needs to know http://api-service.
• Load Balancing: Every time the Python script loops, the ClusterIP service automatically routes the request to one of the 3 available replicas.
• Automation Ready: This is the foundation of how "Collector" or "Scraper" services work in a Kubernetes cluster—using one pod to monitor the health or data of another.
If you delete one of the Nginx pods while the script is running, you'll notice the script keeps working without a hitch because the Service simply directs traffic to the surviving pods.
